&lt;h2 id="memory-addressing">Memory Addressing &lt;a href="#memory-addressing" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true">&lt;i class="material-icons align-middle">link&lt;/i>&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>For better efficiency, a computer&amp;rsquo;s memory is divided into blocks (chunks) called pages. Page size may vary depending on the processor architecture (32 or 64 bits). RAM is divided into page frames. One page frame can contain one page. When a process wants to access a memory address, a translation from the page to the page frame must be performed. If this information is not already in memory, the kernel must perform a search to manually load this page into the page frame.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>